The '''Maui Academy of Performing Arts (MAPA)''' is a nonprofit [[theatre]] company that produces community theater and offers classes to children and young adults. Over the years, the mainstay of the Academy has been their drama, dance, and summer programs.
MAPA was founded in 1974 as the Maui Youth Theater by Linda Takita (daughter of [[Frankie Yankovic]]).<ref name=Farewell> {{cite web | author = Paul Janes-Brown | title = CURTAIN CALL:Farewell to Francie | publisher = The Maui News | url = http://www.mauinews.com/page/content.detail/id/12019.html | date = September 1, 2005 | accessdate = 2008-02-20 }}</ref><ref name=about>{{cite web |author= |title=about MAPA |publisher=MAPA |url=http://www.mauiacademy.org/about/about1.asp?UserID=0 |date= |accessdate=2008-02-20 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080204102843/http://mauiacademy.org/about/about1.asp?UserID=0 |archivedate=2008-02-04 |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref> In 1998 it purchased a {{convert|13000|sqft|m2|abbr=on}}. building in [[Wailuku]] as its main production location.<ref name=newHome>{{cite web | author = Gary T. Kubota | title = Performing arts academy invests in new home | publisher = Honolulu Star-Bulletin.com | url = http://starbulletin.com/98/08/10/news/story8.html | date = August 10, 1998 | accessdate = 2008-02-20 }}</ref> During this time, the Academy has had over 500 productions.<ref name=performances>{{cite web |author= |title=performances and events |publisher=MAPA |url=http://www.mauiacademy.org/performances/performances1.asp?UserID=0 |date= |accessdate=2008-02-20 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080204102930/http://mauiacademy.org/performances/performances1.asp?UserID=0 |archivedate=2008-02-04 |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref> Some notable students and actors are Hawaiian music artists [[Kealiʻi Reichel]], [[Amy Hānaialiʻi Gilliom]], [[Eric Gilliom]], screenwriter [[Gregory Poirier]], and actor, screenwriter, director [[Brian Kohne]].<ref name=newHome/><ref name= home >{{cite web | author = EDWIN TANJI | title = Youth theater finds home in Ka’ahumanu | publisher = The Maui News | url = http://mauinews.com/page/content.detail/id/13442.html | date = October 19, 2005 | accessdate = 2008-02-20 }}</ref>
Every year, the Academy performs for over 25,000 elementary and pre-school students in roughly 200 schools across the state of Hawaii.<ref name=partnerships>{{cite web |author= |title=school partnerships |publisher=MAPA |url=http://www.mauiacademy.org/partnerships/partnerships1.asp?UserID=0 |date= |accessdate=2008-02-20 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080204102913/http://mauiacademy.org/partnerships/partnerships1.asp?UserID=0 |archivedate=2008-02-04 |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref> Its Voices Drama Education Program teaches literacy skills through drama to over 5000 students in Maui County.<ref name="partnerships"/>
The Academy has a yearly summer musical production and a spring dance concert.<ref name=helm>{{cite web | author = PAUL JANES-BROWN | title = CURTAIN CALL: At the helm of MAPA’s big weekend | publisher = The Maui News | url = http://mauinews.com/page/content.detail/id/11195.html | date = August 4, 2005 | accessdate = 2008-02-20 }}</ref> The dance program has attracted guest choreographers from as far away as New York and Los Angeles.<ref name=helm/><ref>{{cite web | author = SKY BARNHART | title = BACKSTAGE: MAPA’s ’Pieces XXIV’ to strike a pose at the MACC | publisher = The Maui News | url = http://mauinews.com/page/content.detail/id/21466.html | date = July 13, 2006 | accessdate = 2008-02-20 }} </ref>
==Donations and grants== As a non-profit organization, the Maui Academy of Performing Arts has received donations and grants from federal, state, and private sources, including the [[National Endowment for the Arts]],<ref name=nea>{{cite web | author = | title = FY 2007 Grant Awards | publisher = NEA | url = http://www.nea.gov/Grants/recent/07grants/ssa07.php | date = | accessdate = 2008-02-20 }}</ref> the [[Hawaii Community Foundation]],<ref name=hcf>{{cite web | author = | title = Funds Established by Donors on Maui Island | publisher = Hawaii Community Foundation | url = http://www.hawaiicommunityfoundation.org/index.php?id=236 | date = | accessdate = 2008-02-20 }}</ref> the [[Samuel N and Mary Castle Foundation]],<ref name=castle>{{cite web | author = | title = Direct Grants and Donations | publisher = Castle Foundation | url = http://foundationcenter.org/grantmaker/castle/06grants.html | date = | accessdate = 2008-02-20 }}</ref> the [[Alexander & Baldwin Foundation]],<ref name=baldwin>{{cite web | author = | title = A&B FOUNDATION CONTRIBUTES OVER $2 MILLION TO CHARITIES IN 2005 | publisher = A&B Foundation | url = http://www.alexanderbaldwinfoundation.org/2005yearend.htm | date = | accessdate = 2008-02-20 }}</ref> the [[McInemy Foundation]],<ref name=xxx>{{cite book | author = | title = Grants for Scholarships | publisher = Jones & Bartlett Publishers | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=uHp6H-hwNUkC&pg=PA728&lpg=PA728&dq=%22maui+academy+of+performing+arts%22+grant&source=web&ots=lYpyc9IgeR&sig=G3rFpNFcSqppToGhGk78eOv_ZKc#PPP1,M1 | date = | accessdate = 2008-02-20 }}</ref> the [[Hawaii Childrens Trust Fund]],<ref name="abuse">{{cite web|url=http://www.molokaitimes.com/articles/72317212.asp|title=Play educates keiki about sexual abuse|author=Allison Devereaux|first=|date=February 3, 2007|website=|publisher=The Molokai Times|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|accessdate=2008-02-20}}</ref> and the [[Children's Justice Center]] <ref name="abuse"/>
==References== {{reflist}} <!-- The following are mostly reviews of performances and probably not useful for the article: {{refbegin}} *{{cite web | author = BRIAN PERRY | title = 'Grand dame of Maui community' dies at 66 | publisher = The Honolulu Advertiser | url = http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2007/Jul/24/br/br5407862139.html | date = July 24, 2007 | accessdate = 2008-02-20 }} *{{cite web | author = SKY BARNHART | title = BACKSTAGE: Arts are good for community’s health ? and its business | publisher = The Maui News | url = http://mauinews.com/page/content.detail/id/33251.html | date = August 16, 2007 | accessdate = 2008-02-20 }} *{{cite web | author = SKY BARNHART | title = The Music Man | publisher = The Maui News | url = http://mauinews.com/page/content.detail/id/500126.html | date = February 8, 2008 | accessdate = 2008-02-20 }} *{{cite web | author = SKY BARNHART | title = MAPA stages the magnificence of the Bard in ’Othello’ | publisher = The Maui News | url = http://mauinews.com/page/content.detail/id/35569.html | date = October 31, 2007 | accessdate = 2008-02-20 }} *{{cite web | author = SKY BARNHART | title = PIECES XXIV: Young dancers strike their poses | publisher = The Maui News | url = http://mauinews.com/page/content.detail/id/21629.html | date = July 19, 2006 | accessdate = 2008-02-20 }} *{{cite web | author = PAUL JANES-BROWN | title = ’Pieces XXIII’: A superb ’Time to Dance’ | publisher = The Maui News | url = http://mauinews.com/page/content.detail/id/11346.html | date = August 10, 2005 | accessdate = 2008-02-20 }} *{{cite web | author = PAUL JANES-BROWN | title = CURTAIN CALL: MAPA’s summer shows highlight Maui’s youthful actors, dancers | publisher = The Maui News | url = http://mauinews.com/page/content.detail/id/10975.html | date = July 28, 2005 | accessdate = 2008-02-20 }} *{{cite web | author = PAUL JANES-BROWN | title = CURTAIN CALL: Island performances hit new heights in 2004 | publisher = The Maui News | url = http://mauinews.